1. Content-Type
Purpose: Specifies the media type (MIME type) of the resource being sent.
Example: Content-Type: application/json
Usage: Helps the server understand the format of the incoming request data or the client to know how to interpret the response.

=======================================

2. Authorization
Purpose: Contains credentials for authenticating a user or a service.
Example: Authorization: Bearer <token>
Usage: Used for securing APIs with tokens (e.g., JWT), API keys, or other authentication methods.

=======================================

3. Accept
Purpose: Informs the server about the media types the client is willing to accept in the response.

=======================================

Example: Accept: application/json
Usage: Clients use it to specify the preferred data format for responses (e.g., JSON, XML, HTML).
4. Cache-Control
Purpose: Specifies caching policies for the client and server.

Example: Cache-Control: no-cache, no-store, must-revalidate

Usage: Controls caching behavior, such as preventing or allowing caches and defining cache expiration rules.

=======================================

5. Content-Length
Purpose: Indicates the size of the request or response body in bytes.
Example: Content-Length: 3495
Usage: Ensures that the client knows how much data is expected and avoids partial responses.

=======================================

6. User-Agent
Purpose: Identifies the client software making the request (e.g., browser, app, or bot).
Example: User-Agent: Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/93.0.4577.82 Safari/537.36
Usage: Helps servers provide client-specific responses (like rendering mobile vs. desktop content).

=======================================

7. Set-Cookie
Purpose: Sends cookies from the server to the client.
Example: Set-Cookie: sessionId=abc123; HttpOnly; Secure
Usage: Used to store session data, authentication tokens, or preferences in the client’s browser.

=======================================

8. Cookie
Purpose: Contains cookies previously sent by the server, which the client now sends back with subsequent requests.
Example: Cookie: sessionId=abc123
Usage: Allows session persistence, where the client sends stored cookies to the server with every request.

=======================================

9. Accept-Encoding
Purpose: Specifies the content encodings that the client can understand.
Example: Accept-Encoding: gzip, deflate, br
Usage: Optimizes responses by compressing them in a format (e.g., gzip) that the client can decompress.

=======================================

10. Content-Disposition
Purpose: Provides instructions for how the content should be displayed or handled (e.g., as an attachment for download).
Example: Content-Disposition: attachment; filename="file.pdf"
Usage: Controls whether the content should be displayed inline or downloaded as a file.

=======================================

11. Origin
Purpose: Identifies the origin of the request for cross-origin resource sharing (CORS) purposes.
Example: Origin: https://example.com
Usage: Helps the server decide whether to allow or block requests from a particular origin (important in CORS).

=======================================

12. Access-Control-Allow-Origin
Purpose: Specifies which origins are allowed to access the resource in cross-origin requests.
Example: Access-Control-Allow-Origin: https://example.com
Usage: Used in CORS to control access to resources by specifying allowed origins.

=======================================

13. Referer (or Referrer)
Purpose: Contains the URL of the page that made the request.
Example: Referer: https://example.com/page1
Usage: Helps the server understand the context of the request (often used in analytics, security, or redirect handling).


=======================================

14. Location
Purpose: Provides a URL to redirect the client to a different location.
Example: Location: https://example.com/new-page
Usage: Used in conjunction with 3xx status codes to redirect the client to a different resource.

=======================================

15. X-Frame-Options
Purpose: Controls whether the browser should allow the content to be embedded in frames (prevents clickjacking).
Example: X-Frame-Options: DENY
Usage: Improves security by preventing the page from being embedded in an iframe.

=======================================

16. X-Content-Type-Options
Purpose: Prevents the browser from interpreting files as a different MIME type than declared.
Example: X-Content-Type-Options: nosniff
Usage: Protects against MIME-type sniffing attacks by ensuring files are handled as their declared type.

=======================================

17. X-XSS-Protection
Purpose: Controls the browser's built-in cross-site scripting (XSS) protection mechanism.
Example: X-XSS-Protection: 1; mode=block
Usage: Adds an extra layer of security by blocking XSS attacks.
18. Content-Security-Policy (CSP)
Purpose: Defines rules to control which resources the client can load and execute (e.g., scripts, styles).
Example: Content-Security-Policy: default-src 'self'; script-src 'none'
Usage: Enhances security by preventing unauthorized scripts or resources from being loaded on a webpage.


=======================================
19. ETag
Purpose: Provides a unique identifier for a specific version of a resource, used in caching.
Example: ETag: "abc123"
Usage: Helps optimize performance by allowing the server to send a resource only if it has been modified.

=======================================

20. If-None-Match
Purpose: The client sends an ETag with this header to check if the resource has changed.
Example: If-None-Match: "abc123"
Usage: If the ETag matches, the server responds with 304 Not Modified, saving bandwidth by avoiding retransmission of unchanged data.
Summary:
Authentication/Authorization: Authorization, Cookie
Caching: Cache-Control, ETag, If-None-Match
Security: X-Frame-Options, X-Content-Type-Options, Content-Security-Policy, X-XSS-Protection
Content: Content-Type, Content-Length, Content-Disposition
CORS: Origin, Access-Control-Allow-Origin
Redirection: Location
Compression: Accept-Encoding
